[2026-05-13 15:36:19,059 - mage.rtl_editor - INFO] RTL editor input message: [ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.SYSTEM: 'system'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nYou are an expert in RTL design.\nYour job is to use actions to edit and simulate SystemVerilog rtl_code,\nTo make sure the edited code has the functionality described in input_spec, and passes the simulation.\nThe actions below are available:\n<actions>\n\n<action>\n<command>replace_content_by_matching</command>\n<signature>(old_content: str, new_content: str) -> Dict[str, Any]</signature>\n<description>\n        Replace the content of the matching line in the file with the new content.\n        Syntax check is performed after the replacement.\n        Please ONLY replace the content that NEEDS to be modified. Don\'t change the content that is correct.\n        Please make sure old_content only occurs once in the file.\n        Input:\n            old_content: The old content of the file.\n            new_content: The new content to replace the matching line.\n        Output:\n            A dictionary containing :\n                1. Whether the action is executed.\n                2. The error message if the action is not executed.\n                3. Other information like syntax check result and simulation check result.\n        Example:\n            Before:\n            <example_rtl>\n                1 module test;\n                2   reg a;\n                3   reg b;\n                4 endmodule\n            </example_rtl>\n            Action:\n            <action_input>\n                "command": "replace_content_by_matching",\n                "args": {\n                    "old_content": "  reg a;\n  reg b;",\n                    "new_content": "  logic a;",\n                },\n            </action_input>\n            Now:\n            <example_rtl>\n                1 module test;\n                2   logic a;\n                4 endmodule\n            </example_rtl>\n        </description>\n</action>\n\n</actions>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nThe information below is give to help your work:\n1. The input_spec specifing the functionality of the RTL module;\n2. The generated testbench, which is verified correct by another LLM judge;\n3. The log generated by the simulation which is failed by the generated RTL and TB.\n<input_spec>\n\nI would like you to implement a module named TopModule with the following\ninterface. All input and output ports are one bit unless otherwise\nspecified.\n\n - input  clock\n - input  a\n - output p\n - output q\n\nThe module should implement a sequential circuit. Read the simulation\nwaveforms to determine what the circuit does, then implement it.\n\n  time   clock   a   p   q\n  0ns    0       0   x   x\n  5ns    0       0   x   x\n  10ns   0       0   x   x\n  15ns   0       0   x   x\n  20ns   0       0   x   x\n  25ns   1       0   0   x\n  30ns   1       0   0   x\n  35ns   1       0   0   x\n  40ns   1       0   0   x\n  45ns   1       0   0   x\n  50ns   1       0   0   x\n  55ns   0       0   0   0\n  60ns   0       0   0   0\n  65ns   0       0   0   0\n  70ns   0       1   0   0\n  75ns   0       0   0   0\n  80ns   0       1   0   0\n  85ns   1       0   0   0\n  90ns   1       1   1   0\n  95ns   1       0   0   0\n  100ns  1       1   1   0\n  105ns  1       0   0   0\n  110ns  1       1   1   0\n  115ns  0       0   1   1\n  120ns  0       1   1   1\n  125ns  0       0   1   1\n  130ns  0       1   1   1\n  135ns  0       0   1   1\n  140ns  0       0   1   1\n  145ns  1       0   0   1\n  150ns  1       0   0   1\n  155ns  1       0   0   1\n  160ns  1       0   0   1\n  165ns  1       1   1   1\n  170ns  1       0   0   1\n  175ns  0       1   0   0\n  180ns  0       0   0   0\n  185ns  0       1   0   0\n  190ns  0       0   0   0\n\n\n</input_spec>\n<generated_tb>\n`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\n`define OK 12\n`define INCORRECT 13\n\nmodule stimulus_gen (\n\tinput clk,\n\toutput logic clock=0,\n\toutput logic a,\n\toutput logic [511:0] wavedrom_title,\n\toutput logic wavedrom_enable\n);\n\n\talways begin\n\t\trepeat(3) @(posedge clk);\n\t\tclock = ~clock;\n\tend\n\n\ttask wavedrom_start(input[511:0] title = "");\n\tendtask\n\t\n\ttask wavedrom_stop;\n\t\t#1;\n\tendtask\t\n\n\tinitial begin\n\t\ta <= 0;\n\t\t@(negedge clock) {a} <= 0;\n\t\t@(negedge clk) wavedrom_start("Unknown circuit");\n\t\t\t@(posedge clk) {a} <= 0;\n\t\t\trepeat(14) @(posedge clk,negedge clk) a <= ~a;\n\t\t\trepeat(5) @(posedge clk, negedge clk);\n\t\t\trepeat(8) @(posedge clk,negedge clk) a <= ~a;\n\t\twavedrom_stop();\n\n\t\trepeat(200) @(posedge clk, negedge clk)\n\t\t\ta <= $urandom;\n\t\t$finish;\n\tend\n\t\nendmodule\n\nmodule tb();\n\n\ttypedef struct packed {\n\t\tint errors;\n\t\tint errortime;\n\t\tint errors_p;\n\t\tint errortime_p;\n\t\tint errors_q;\n\t\tint errortime_q;\n\n\t\tint clocks;\n\t} stats;\n\t\n\tstats stats1;\n\t\n\t\n\twire[511:0] wavedrom_title;\n\twire wavedrom_enable;\n\tint wavedrom_hide_after_time;\n\t\n\treg clk=0;\n\tinitial forever\n\t\t#5 clk = ~clk;\n\n\tlogic clock;\n\tlogic a;\n\tlogic p_ref;\n\tlogic p_dut;\n\tlogic q_ref;\n\tlogic q_dut;\n\n\tinitial begin \n\t\t$dumpfile("wave.vcd");\n\t\t$dumpvars(1, stim1.clk, tb_mismatch ,clock,a,p_ref,p_dut,q_ref,q_dut );\n\tend\n\n\twire tb_match;\t\t// Verification\n\twire tb_mismatch = ~tb_match;\n\t\n\tstimulus_gen stim1 (\n\t\t.clk,\n\t\t.* ,\n\t\t.clock,\n\t\t.a );\n\tRefModule good1 (\n\t\t.clock,\n\t\t.a,\n\t\t.p(p_ref),\n\t\t.q(q_ref) );\n\t\t\n\tTopModule top_module1 (\n\t\t.clock,\n\t\t.a,\n\t\t.p(p_dut),\n\t\t.q(q_dut) );\n\n\n\tbit strobe = 0;\n\ttask wait_for_end_of_timestep;\n\t\trepeat(5) begin\n\t\t\tstrobe <= !strobe;  // Try to delay until the very end of the time step.\n\t\t\t@(strobe);\n\t\tend\n\tendtask\t\n\n\tassign tb_match = ( { p_ref, q_ref } === ( { p_ref, q_ref } ^ { p_dut, q_dut } ^ { p_ref, q_ref } ) );\n\n\t// Use explicit sensitivity list here. @(*) causes NetProc::nex_input() to be called when trying to compute\n\t// the sensitivity list of the @(strobe) process, which isn\'t implemented.\n\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\n\t\tstats1.clocks++;\n\t\tif (!tb_match) begin\n\t\t\tif (stats1.errors == 0) stats1.errortime = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors++;\n\t\t\tend\n\t\tif (p_ref !== ( p_ref ^ p_dut ^ p_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_p == 0) stats1.errortime_p = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors_p = stats1.errors_p+1\'b1; end\n\t\tif (q_ref !== ( q_ref ^ q_dut ^ q_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_q == 0) stats1.errortime_q = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors_q = stats1.errors_q+1\'b1; end\n\n\tend\n\n\t// Display for first mismatch\n\t// We use a separate process or a flag to ensure it only prints once\n\t// But the requirement says \'When the first mismatch occurs, display...\' \n\t// To avoid duplicates in the always block, we use a bit flag.\n\tbit mismatch_reported = 0;\n\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\t\tif (!tb_match && !mismatch_reported) begin\n\t\t\tmismatch_reported = 1;\n\t\t\t$display("FIRST MISMATCH DETECTED at time %0t:", $time);\n\t\t\t$display("Inputs: clock=%b, a=%b", clock, a);\n\t\t\t$display("Expected: p=%b, q=%b", p_ref, q_ref);\n\t\t\t$display("Actual:   p=%b, q=%b", p_dut, q_dut);\n\t\tend\n\tend\n\n\n\t// add timeout after 100K cycles\n\tinitial begin\n\t  #1000000\n\t  $display("TIMEOUT");\n\t  $finish();\n\tend\n\n\tfinal begin\n\t\tif (stats1.errors == 0) $display("SIMULATION PASSED");\n\t\telse $display("SIMULATION FAILED - %0d MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME %0d", stats1.errors, stats1.errortime);\n\n\t\tif (stats1.errors_p) $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has %0d mismatches. First mismatch occurred at time %0d.", "p", stats1.errors_p, stats1.errortime_p);\n\t\telse $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has no mismatches.", "p");\n\t\tif (stats1.errors_q) $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has %0d mismatches. First mismatch occurred at time %0d.", "q", stats1.errors_q, stats1.errortime_q);\n\t\telse $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has no mismatches.", "q");\n\n\t\t$display("Hint: Total mismatched samples is %1d out of %1d samples\\n", stats1.errors, stats1.clocks);\n\t\t$display("Simulation finished at %0d ps", $time);\n\t\t$display("Mismatches: %1d in %1d samples", stats1.errors, stats1.clocks);\n\tend\n\nendmodule\n</generated_tb>\n<sim_failed_log>\n{\n    "stdout": "VCD info: dumpfile wave.vcd opened for output.\\nFIRST MISMATCH DETECTED at time 120:\\nInputs: clock=0, a=0\\nExpected: p=1, q=1\\nActual:   p=0, q=0\\n./output_t22b_gemma4_26b_shard4_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob145_circuit8/tb.sv:37: $finish called at 1200 (1ps)\\nSIMULATION FAILED - 143 MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME 120\\nHint: Output \'p\' has 92 mismatches. First mismatch occurred at time 120.\\nHint: Output \'q\' has 109 mismatches. First mismatch occurred at time 120.\\nHint: Total mismatched samples is 143 out of 240 samples\\n\\nSimulation finished at 1200 ps\\nMismatches: 143 in 240 samples\\n",\n    "stderr": ""\n}\n</sim_failed_log>\n\n[Hints]:\nFor implementing kmap (Karnaugh map), you need to think and solve mismatches step by step.\nFind the inputs corresponding to mismatch in sim_failed_log, and set the output to correct value while maintaining other outputs.\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.ASSISTANT: 'assistant'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{\n    "reasoning": "The input spec provides a waveform that shows the behavior of the circuit. Let\'s trace the waveform to determine the state machine and outputs.\\n\\nWaveform analysis:\\n- Time 25-50ns: clock=1, a=0, p=0, q=x (initially p=0, q=0 after 55ns).\\n- Time 55-70ns: clock=0/1, a=0, p=0, q=0. State seems to be a \'reset\' or \'idle\' state.\\n- Time 70-80ns: a=1, p=0, q=0. Next clock cycle (85ns) a=0, p=0, q=0. Next clock cycle (90ns) a=1, p=1, q=0. \\n- Wait, let\'s look at the transitions at clock edges (rising edges).\\n- 85ns (posedge): a=0, p=0, q=0. (Previous a=1 at 80ns, p=0, q=0)\\n- 90ns (posedge): a=1, p=1, q=0. (Previous a=0 at 85ns, p=0, q=0)\\n- 95ns (posedge): a=0, p=0, q=0. (Previous a=1 at 90ns, p=1, q=0)\\n- 100ns (posedge): a=1, p=1, q=0. (Previous a=0 at 95ns, p=0, q=0)\\n- 110ns (posedge): a=1, p=1, q=0. (Previous a=0 at 105ns, p=0, q=0)\\n- 115ns (negedge): p=1, q=1. This is unusual. The waveform shows values changing at 115ns (negedge).\\n- 115ns: a=0, p=1, q=1.\\n- 120ns: a=1, p=1, q=1.\\n- 130ns: a=1, p=1, q=1.\\n- 145ns: a=0, p=0, q=1.\\n- 165ns: a=1, p=1, q=1.\\n- 175ns: a=1, p=0, q=0.\\n\\nLooking closely at the outputs:\\n- p seems to track \'a\' but with some delay or condition. \\n- Actually, looking at the sequence:\\n  When a=1 (at 90, 100, 110), p=1 and q=0.\\n  Then at 115 (negedge), p=1 and q=1. This suggests q becomes 1 after a certain number of \'a\' pulses or some condition.\\n  At 145, a=0, p=0, q=1. So q stays 1 even if p becomes 0.\\n  At 165, a=1, p=1, q=1.\\n  At 175, a=1, p=0, q=0. (q drops back to 0).\\n\\nLet\'s re-evaluate the sequence of \'a\' values at clock edges:\\n- 85ns: a=0\\n- 90ns: a=1 -> p=1, q=0\\n- 95ns: a=0 -> p=0, q=0\\n- 100ns: a=1 -> p=1, q=0\\n- 105ns: a=0 -> p=0, q=0\\n- 110ns: a=1 -> p=1, q=0\\n- 115ns: (negedge) p=1, q=1. This is very strange. Usually, outputs change on edges. Let\'s assume it\'s a state machine where p and q depend on the state.\\n\\nLet\'s try to model the state transition based on \'a\'.\\n- State 0: p=0, q=0. If a=1, go to State 1.\\n- State 1: p=a, q=0. If a=1, stay in State 1 or go to State 2? If a=0, go to State 0.\\n- State 2: p=1, q=1. If a=1, stay in State 2. If a=0, go to State 3?\\n- State 3: p=a, q=1. If a=0, go to State 4? If a=1, go to State 2?\\n\\nLet\'s look at the transition around 110ns-115ns again.\\nAt 110ns, a=1, p=1, q=0. At 115ns, p=1, q=1. This transition happens at a negedge? No, the waveform shows a=0 at 115ns. The 115ns mark is a negedge.\\nWait, the input spec says: \\n110ns  1       1       1       0\\n115ns  0       0       1       1\\n120ns  0       1       1       1\\n\\nThis means at 110ns (posedge), a=1, p=1, q=0. Between 110ns and 115ns (negedge), p and q change? That\'s only possible if they are combinational and depend on \'a\' or if the state changes on negedge. But the clock is 10ns period. 110ns is posedge, 115ns is negedge.\\n\\nWait, if p and q are combinational, they can change at 115ns if \'a\' changes at 115ns. But \'a\' is 0 at 115ns and was 0 at 105ns. So \'a\' didn\'t change at 115ns. \\nThis implies the state changed at 115ns (negedge).\\n\\nLet\'s re-examine the waveform carefully.\\nAt 110ns: clock=1, a=1, p=1, q=0.\\nAt 115ns: clock=0, a=0, p=1, q=1.\\nAt 120ns: clock=0, a=1, p=1, q=1.\\nAt 145ns: clock=1, a=0, p=0, q=1.\\nAt 165ns: clock=1, a=1, p=1, q=1.\\nAt 170ns: clock=1, a=0, p=0, q=1.\\nAt 175ns: clock=0, a=1, p=0, q=0.\\n\\nIf state changes on negedge:\\nAt 115ns (negedge), q becomes 1. This happened when a was 0 and p was 1? No, p was 1 at 110ns and remains 1 at 115ns.\\n\\nLet\'s try a different approach. What if the state machine is:\\nState 0 (Idle): p=0, q=0. Transition to State 1 if a=1.\\nState 1 (Detecting): p=a, q=0. Transition to State 2 if a=1 AND we have seen a=1 previously? \\nActually, looking at 90, 100, 110: p=1 when a=1. This looks like p = a (with some delay or state).\\nAt 110ns, a=1, p=1, q=0. The next step is q=1. \\nIt looks like q becomes 1 after three consecutive (or non-consecutive?) a=1 pulses.\\n\\nLet\'s look at the transitions for q:\\n- q=0 until 115ns (negedge).\\n- q=1 from 115ns to 175ns.\\n- q=0 after 175ns (negedge).\\n\\nWhen does q become 1? At 115ns, which is the negedge after a sequence of a=1.\\nSequence of a at posedges: 90(a=1), 100(a=1), 110(a=1). That\'s three \'a\'s.\\nWhen does q become 0? At 175ns (negedge). \\nSequence of a at posedges after q=1: 165(a=1), 170(a=0).\\nWait, at 175ns (negedge), a=1, but p and q both become 0.\\n\\nLet\'s try to implement a state machine that tracks the number of \'a\' pulses.\\nState 0: q=0, p=0. If a=1, goto State 1.\\nState 1: q=0, p=a. If a=1, goto State 2. If a=0, goto State 0.\\nState 2: q=0, p=a. If a=1, goto State 3. If a=0, goto State 1.\\nState 3: q=1, p=a. If a=1, goto State 2. If a=0, goto State 4? No.\\n\\nActually, let\'s look at the output p again. \\nAt 115ns, p=1 even though a=0. \\nAt 120ns, a=1, p=1. \\nAt 145ns, a=0, p=0. \\nAt 165ns, a=1, p=1.\\nAt 170ns, a=0, p=0.\\nAt 175ns, a=1, p=0. (This is a mismatch with p=a).\\n\\nThis suggests p and q are driven by the state, and the state changes on negedge or posedge.\\nGiven the waveform, let\'s try to use a state machine that transitions on both edges or just use a simpler logic.\\nActually, many of these behaviors can be described by a state machine that transitions on posedge and has outputs that depend on the current state and \'a\'.\\n\\nLet\'s re-trace q: \\nIt stays 0 while a is being pulsed. After the 3rd pulse (at 110ns), at the next negedge (115ns), q becomes 1.\\nIt stays 1 as long as a is pulsed or 0. \\nAt 170ns, a=0. At 175ns (negedge), q becomes 0. This is after a=0 at 170ns.\\n\\nLet\'s try this:\\nState 0: p=0, q=0. If a=1, goto State 1.\\nState 1: p=a, q=0. If a=1, goto State 2. If a=0, goto State 0.\\nState 2: p=a, q=0. If a=1, goto State 3. If a=0, goto State 1.\\nState 3: p=a, q=1. If a=1, goto State 2. If a=0, goto State 4.\\nState 4: p=0, q=1. If a=1, goto State 0. If a=0, goto State 4.\\n\\nWait, let\'s check 175ns. At 170ns, a=0. If we are in State 4, q=1. At 175ns (negedge), q becomes 0. This would happen if the state transitions on negedge.\\n\\nLet\'s try a state machine that transitions on posedge and we\'ll see if we can match the negedge behavior.\\nIf the state machine transitions on posedge, we can\'t easily explain the 115ns negedge change unless the outputs are combinational and depend on \'a\', but \'a\' doesn\'t change at 115ns. \\nUnless... the state transition is on negedge.\\n\\nIf state transitions on negedge:\\n- 110ns: posedge, a=1, state stays in State 2.\\n- 115ns: negedge, a=0, state moves from State 2 to State 3.\\n- State 3: p=1, q=1. (Matches 115ns-130ns).\\n- 145ns: posedge, a=0, state stays in State 3.\\n- 165ns: posedge, a=1, state stays in State 3.\\n- 170ns: posedge, a=0, state stays in State 3.\\n- 175ns: negedge, a=1, state moves from State 3 to State 0.\\n- State 0: p=0, q=0. (Matches 180ns).\\n\\nThis looks promising! Let\'s refine the states with negedge transition:\\nState 0 (Idle): p=0, q=0. \\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 1.\\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 0.\\nState 1 (First pulse): p=a, q=0. \\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 2.\\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 0.\\nState 2 (Second pulse): p=a, q=0. \\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 3. \\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 1.\\nState 3 (Third pulse/q=1): p=1, q=1. (Wait, 115ns a=0, p=1, q=1, so p is 1).\\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 2.\\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 4?\\nState 4 (Resetting q): p=0, q=1. \\n  If a=1 at negedge -> State 0.\\n  If a=0 at negedge -> State 4.\\n\\nWait, let\'s check State 3 p value. At 115ns, a=0 and p=1. At 120ns, a=1 and p=1. So in State 3, p=1.\\nAt 145ns, a=0 and p=0. This means State 3 is not quite right. \\nAt 145ns, a=0, p=0, q=1. This matches State 4.\\nSo at 115ns (negedge), if a=0, we go to State 4. \\nState 4: p=a, q=1. \\nLet\'s check: 145ns: a=0, p=0, q=1. (Matches State 4).\\n165ns: a=1, p=1, q=1. (Matches State 4).\\n170ns: a=0, p=0, q=1. (Matches State 4).\\n175ns: negedge, a=1. If in State 4 and a=1, go to State 0. \\nState 0: p=0, q=0. (Matches 180ns).\\n\\nLet\'s re-verify State 2:\\nAt 110ns, a=1, p=1, q=0. (State 2).\\nAt 115ns, a=0, p=1, q=1. (State 4).\\nWait, if state transition is on negedge, at 115ns (negedge) a=0, so we move from State 2 to State 4.\\nState 2: p=1 (since a=1 at 110ns), q=0.\\nState 4: p=a, q=1. \\nAt 115ns, a=0, so p=0? But the waveform says p=1 at 115ns. \\nThis means p is 1 at 115